-- South African Stocks Climb For a Third Day, Led Higher by Anglo and Kumba
-- Janice Kew
-- 2010-07-22T10:08:28Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-22/south-african-stocks-climb-for-a-third-day-led-higher-by-anglo-and-kumba.html

          
          
             South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for a third day, gaining 221.34, or 0.8
percent, to 28,054.86 at 11:32 a.m. in Johannesburg.  
 The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  
 Absolute Holdings Ltd.  (ABO SJ) rallied 70 cents, or 25
percent, to 3.50 rand, the biggest intraday increase in more
than five months, after the mining company raised 24.8 million
rand ($3.3 million).  
 ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd.  (ACL SJ), Africa’s largest
steel producer, gained 2.48 rand, or 3.1 percent, to 81.58 rand,
bringing its rise so far this week to 13 percent. Kumba Iron Ore
Ltd. said it reached an interim agreement for deliveries of the
steelmaking ingredient to ArcelorMittal South Africa, while
arbitration over a supply dispute continues.  
 Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ) climbed 5.50 rand, or 2
percent, to 283.50 rand, extending yesterday’s 1.5 percent gain.
 BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining company,
advanced 2.36 rand, or 1.1 percent, to 222.36 rand. Copper for
delivery in three months rose 0.5 percent to $6,892 a metric ton
on the London Metal Exchange for its fourth day of gains.  
 Separately, Australia’s proposed tax on iron ore and coal
mine profits favors Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton Ltd. and
Xstrata Plc over smaller producers, according to  Andrew Forrest ,
the chief executive officer of Fortescue Metals Group Ltd.  
 Kumba Iron Ore Ltd.  (KIO SJ) increased 10.31 rand, or 2.8
percent, to 372.81 rand. A close at this price would be the
highest in more than three months. The iron ore producer that is
owned by Anglo American Plc said first-half earnings excluding
one-time items jumped to 6.49 billion rand ($859 million) from
3.44 billion rand the same period a year earlier.  
 Petmin Ltd.  (PET SJ) advanced the most in more than two
months, rising 24 cents, or 9.8 percent, to 2.69 rand. The
country’s largest anthracite coal miner said it will double its
coal processing capacity to 1.1 million metric tons a year with
the construction of a second plant in South Africa.  
 Vodacom Group Ltd.  (VOD SJ) dropped 93 cents, or 1.5
percent, to 61.87 rand, headed for the biggest drop in three
weeks. The largest provider of mobile phone services to South
Africans said the number of subscribers fell 8.7 percent to 37.7
million in the first quarter from the same period a year
earlier.  
